Add support for JetBrains IDEs (#148)

This commit adds a new jetbrains directory with the included
Dracula.icls file. This file was generated from the existing
Dracula.tmTheme using the JetBrains colorSchemeTool.

In theory, this color scheme should work for all JetBrains/IntelliJ
IDEs, but I have only been able to test it with PyCharm, where it
appears to be working nicely. We may want to find some other folks to
test it out in other JetBrains IDEs.

Merge pull request #136 from eigengrau/master

Emacs improvements

Emacs: theme trailing whitespace consistently.

Emacs has two ways to show trailing whitespace. In any mode, one may set
show-trailing-whitespace to “t”, which will cause trailing whitespace to
use trailing-whitespace face. Or, more elaborately, one may use
whitespace-mode, which uses whitespace-trailing face. whitespace-mode
uses “red1” by default, but we want both faces look the same, so we let
the latter inherit from the former.

Emacs: improve isearch faces.

By default, isearch-fail doesn’t set a foreground color and will thus inherit
the default white text foreground. This will be illegible on top of the
warning-colored background, so we explicitly set the foreground color now.

Emacs: improve ido-support.

Directories in ido default to “red1”, which is less than pleasing in contrast to
the dracula background.

Emacs: set which-func-mode-face.

which-func-mode uses a horrible heuristics to define the face used on
the mode-line. Notably, when using dracula theme, which-func-mode-face
will have foreground color Blue1, which is an eyesore when combined with
dracula theme.

This fixes the problem by making sure we are using the same foreground
as function-names.

Use actual filename casing

On OSX, by default, the filesystem is case-preserving, so locating
Dracula works fine. However, many linux filesystems are case-sensitive
so `colorscheme Dracula` causes the colorscheme to not be found.
